04346nam a22006615i 9780824874582DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20052005hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248745827 a10.1515/97808248745822doi  a(DE-B1597)483875  a(OCoLC)1076416764  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aART0190002bisacsh1 aFowler, Sherry D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMuroji :bRearranging Art and History at a Japanese Buddhist Temple /cSherry D. Fowler. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (312 p.) :bcolor & b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one. Below the Surface of Mt. Murō -- tChapter two. Religious Affiliations and Contested Histories -- tChapter three. The Building and Rebuilding of Murōji -- tChapter four. Outside and Inside the Golden Hall -- tChapter five. Shifting Identities and Trading Places in the Golden Hall -- tConclusion: Manifestation of Multiplicity -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Japanese and Chinese characters -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMurōji, a magnificent temple founded in the eighth century, is known both for its dramatic location and the exceptional quality of its ritual objects and art dating from the ninth and tenth centuries of the Heian period. Sherry Fowler makes extensive use of primary sources to explore the circumstances surrounding the creation and function of the temple’s main images and considers why major works of early Heian sculpture were housed in such a remote mountain setting. Employing a multifaceted approach that looks at Murōji’s art and architecture in socio-political context, she explores the establishment of the temple, its role in the religious life and power structure of the region, and the ways in which the temple reconfigured its early history to suit its later circumstances. Emerging from Fowler’s study are pervasive themes relating to worship and practice at Murōji that highlight plurality of practice (of different schools of Buddhism as well as Shinto); flexibility of practice and its impact on sculptural icons; the relationship of Murōji to other temple/shrine complexes; and the association of the temple with women’s worship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082487458240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824874582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824874582/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK